I. INTRODUCTION¶

Given a list of news weblinks, our group shall be using the unsupervised modelling for Topic Modelling by using the Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) model to determine what are the topics generated by simply having the web address. We will attempt to make sense of such grouping.

II. DATASET¶

The dataset is taken from the UCLA website under the News Aggregator machine learning problem. You may click here to be redirected to the page.

Dataset is comprised of two files. The below name and schema are lifted from the website and will shall be elaborated after.

FIRST DATASET: newsCorpora.csv

ID Numeric ID
TITLE News title
URL Url
PUBLISHER Publisher name
CATEGORY News category (b = business, t = science and technology, e = entertainment, m = health)
STORY Alphanumeric ID of the cluster that includes news about the same story
HOSTNAME Url hostname
TIMESTAMP Approximate time the news was published, as the number of milliseconds since the epoch 00:00:00 GMT, January 1, 1970

SECOND DATASET: 2pageSessions.csv

HOSTNAME Url hostname
STORY Alphanumeric ID of the cluster that includes news about the same story
HOSTNAME Url hostname
CATEGORY News category (b = business, t = science and technology, e = entertainment, m = health)
URL Two space-delimited urls representing a browsing session

For the first dataset, we will look into the TITLE. But as we shall see below, some of the titles will not be useful so we will do data cleaning to sort these out and replace them with their corresponding URL.

For the second dataset, we will solely be relying on the URL. As we shall see below, the main issue for the second dataset are the duplicates.

After which, we shall consolidate both and perform LDA.

III. PROBLEM STATEMENT¶

Primary: Beyond the current categories provided, can we create a new and descriptive groupings of the articles to determine what types of news are being released on the internet?

Secondary: Is there a possibility that certain hostname/urls are leaning towards a certain topic?

The secondary problem statement was not attempted in this run. Suggest to have look into this after.

IV. METHODS¶

This project would be using the LDA (Latent Dirichlet Allocation) model to group these websites into the topic resulted from the mining.

V. LOADING THE DATA¶

We have two sets of data:

  1. First dataset of URLs over 400k+ with the news article title carved out properly. Only issue is that some of the entries in the TITLE column is "Posted by". This means we only have the author but not what the article is about. This data needs to be trasformed.

  2. Second dataset of URLs over 10k+ without the news article title. Since we need to do NLP, transformation is needed.

Also both datasets have duplicates so we need to remove them.

def freq_words(x, terms = 10):
  all_words = ' '.join([text for text in x])
  all_words = all_words.split()
  
  fdist = FreqDist(all_words)
  words_df = pd.DataFrame({'word':list(fdist.keys()), 'count':list(fdist.values())})
  
  # selecting top 20 most frequent words
  d = words_df.nlargest(columns='count', n = terms) 
  plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
  ax = sns.barplot(data=d, x= 'count', y = 'word', palette = 'GnBu_d')
  ax.set(xlabel = 'COUNT',ylabel = 'WORD')
  plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 15})
  plt.show()

nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_md', disable=['parser', 'ner'])

def lemmatization(texts,allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ']): 
       output = []
       for sent in texts:
             doc = nlp(sent) 
             output.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags ])
       return output

Coherence score for multiple topics¶

In [65]:
def compute_coherence_values(dictionary, corpus, texts, limit, start=2, step=3):
    """
    Compute c_v coherence for various number of topics

    Parameters:
    ----------
    dictionary : Gensim dictionary
    corpus : Gensim corpus
    texts : List of input texts
    limit : Max num of topics

    Returns:
    -------
    model_list : List of LDA topic models
    coherence_values : Coherence values corresponding to the LDA model with respective number of topics
    """
    coherence_values = []
    model_list = []
    for num_topics in range(start, limit, step):
        model = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus=corpus, num_topics=num_topics, id2word=dictionary)
        model_list.append(model)
        coherencemodel = CoherenceModel(model=model, texts=texts, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
        coherence_values.append(coherencemodel.get_coherence())

    return model_list, coherence_values

VIII. INSIGHTS¶

  1. Topics formed: Cluster 1 Finance and Marketing
    Cluster 2 Global Trends
    Cluster 3 Crime, Disease & Natural Disaster
    Cluster 4 Music, TV and Entertainment
    Cluster 5 Movies, TV, and Entertainment
    Cluster 6 Recent Developments

  2. Cluster 4 and 6 overlaps which means their topic seem to have similarities. We can consider updating our stopwords to remove those words causing this overlap OR identify how they can be differentiated. Other clusters are easily distinguishable and identifiable. Upon putting New and News as stopwords and looking at five topics, we have:

  3. Old categories: business, science and technology, entertainment, health. New categories seem to be more descriptive. Also entertainment seem to have a large scope worth to break down into more than one category.

  4. LDA model does not account the ‘sense’ or the correlation of each w for each d. In our case, the model seem fit since scraping internet URLs would not necessarily form sensible phrases.
